I LOVED this, and girl I can relate! I'm from a highly sought after tourist town in Ontario Canada by the Blue Mountains called Collingwood. It's right at the base of the mountain.  It's popular for craft beer...skiing, waterfront etc. I grew up here and moved back after college thinking I could get a one bedroom for the same price as I could get in small city I was in during college. HAAAAA I was in for a shock! We almost have New York or Toronto prices here in Collingwood! I want to settle down in my hometown because it's literally the best place I've ever lived and I've lived in so many surrounding towns and cities. But man....the struggle is real even in Canada. Within the past 13 years it has become severely gentrified! It has a lot of history. It is the last stop in Canada for the underground railroad, it is one of the Country's oldest shipyards. My uncle used to be one of the shipmen before he joined the navy, and it has now become a place for rich retiring Toronto business people to buy up real estate and rent out Air Bnb's....making it almost impossible for young people to live here. It makes me so sad :/ <3 And it happened SO quickly while I was away in College!  I had no idea what I was up against when I decided to move back home...I really hope the renting problem gets balanced out soon because young people are getting screwed left right and center it feels! I know I'm not the only one who feels this way....I'd move out west but all I have at the moment is my family, and now I have to take care of my sick mom who is not in a position to move anywhere. I hope things get better for my generation. I know so many beautiful people who would be content and humble with a small space to call home!

Itâ€™s very difficult to try to find AND secure an apartment months in advance in NYC. Apartments are constantly being snatched up in NYC and it can be sort of demoralizing. Searching and getting an idea of areas youâ€™d like to live in is fineâ€” but honestly it is such a case by case situation here. If you work minimum wage (which is $15/hr) in NYC you might be declined even the opportunity to hold a deposit on an apartment. MANY places ESPECIALLY in Manhattan need you to be making 40x the rent and have a good credit score. Otherwise you need to have a guarantor that makes an even GREATER amount of money than 40x the rent. You might be able to find something in Brooklyn, Queens, or Harlem that would be a little easier on the rent capâ€” but at $1,650(my 1 bdrm rent in bay ridge)x40â€“ both my boyfriend and I barely had enough combined income to qualify. SO make sure to save your money to be able to prove youâ€™d be able to pay rent if you sign a lease. :)

I almost cried when she said she payed a brokers fee. I've lived in NYC for years and have never paid a broker. It's a complete scam and what she didn't note is that most leases state that each time you renew you're lease you have to repay the broker fee which is usually 10-15% of the yearly rent. Meaning you're paying that broker every year until you move out of that apt. So, if you stay there for years, which most New Yorkers do because you don't leave a good "cheap" apt in the city because rent prices across the city go up every year. I've been in my apt for 5+ yrs and they'd have to drag me out kicking and screaming lmao. My point is please don't pay broker fees you can rent apt's in the city without paying a broker, their not necessary.

Broker fees were always optional because you donâ€™t HAVE to work with a broker and you can always choose to see â€œno feeâ€ apartments. The law now forces forces building management/owners to pay the broker when there is one. Anyone thatâ€™s paid a broker fee after June 14th, 2019 is eligible for reimbursement. Â @DreamCloud124Â  Well for now agents can still charge a broker's fee. A judge temporarily blocked that ruling from being in effect because of uproar from the Real Estate Board of NYC. They believe the Department of State is in violation of their rights essentially when they stated Landlords/Building Management have to pay the broker's fee. I believe what is illegal now is real estate asking for an extra month's rent deposit.  The June 2019 law was tweaked January of this year so it states we are NOT due for a refund of a broker's fee. Native New Yorker. Many apartments do not have a broker fee, and the ones with fees can be negotiated. Oftentimes, the building or landlord is willing to cover the fee if you can prove you'll be a stable tenant. I wouldn't pay a fee unless there was a spectacular deal that the broker got for you. My 1st apartment in NY had a broker fee of 1 month, but the broker got us 3 months rent-free, which was a great deal. We also negotiated $1,000 off his fee when we told him we would apply same day. So have your financial affairs in order before you look.

As an actual  lifelong New Yorker, here are some tips. People from out of town get ripped off severely. ALWAYS negotiate rent prices. NEVER just pay what they tell you. A common negotiation is $25-$50 lower rent to sign for a 2 year lease. You can even use how quickly you're willing to sign a lease as leverage. I pay 1700, for an apartment 3x the size as Ashley's in Brooklyn. People moving here who just take whatever they're handed are the ones who make prices rise for all of us, just because they're constantly getting ripped off and landlords there are plenty of people who don't know any better who are willing to pay way more than they should. Another tip is checking the public records for buildings. You can google it and see all city documents including information about pests, and other issues in the building. Always use that to your advantage.

I'm 26 and I live with a roommate on the upper east side, we got lucky with 2k a month, split right down the middle.. the thing is, NYC rent is more, but you make more, so it evens out. Most people who live in NYC when they are in their 20s have to have a roomate, unless your parents make a crap ton of $$ and you get lucky.. then they end up moving out of the city when it's time to "Settle down" , either moving to another part of NY State or a cheaper state because it gets old after a while and it's unattainable, but the experience is fun and the job experience of working in NYC will always look impressive. My friend and I work corporate finance companies in the city as well, so it may depend on your field of work you are in, but again, you make more money in NYC, so it evens out. Also, most people, at least young adults, don't own a car when living in the city so that can help out too.

In NYC, you pay the fees and taxes while renting as it is rolled into the rent. Apartments are tiny. In other places you can afford a house with a yard, off street parking, shop online, avoid the crowds, etc. When a mortgage is paid off, the payments end, but you get to stay, unlike rent anywhere.  Sure taxes, insurance, utilities still exist, but being your own landlord is a good part of financial planning. I make less than I could living in NY, but it buys a lot more. I live in a 5 bedroom 3 bath home with 20 X 30 shop, hot tub, fireplace, rose garden, etc. I have visited NYC, and could again, if I ever wanted to. I'd rather drive to the mountains nearby and enjoy myself. If I want culture, there are tons of microbrews, theater, comedy clubs, ballet, opera, concerts, museums, etc.

That means no street facing windows, if it absolutely has to face the street, make sure its a street and not an avenue, make sure it is on the fourth floor or above. It amazes me how different the rental system is in the US. Here in Australia it's so different. First of all, weekly rent, not monthly. Brokers fee, why would the tenant pay that? The landlord is the one hiring the services of the real estate to rent out their property, for them to make money.   Then the application process is a little different. The documents you provide are pretty much the same, but I've never heard of the 40x income amount. There is no application fee, most of the applications are done online. The security deposit (called bond here) is 4 weeks worth of rent and paid only once accepted.   Depending on the real estate you apply with, applications can take a couple of days or even a week to process. Usually multiple applicants have applied, they are short listed by the real estate and passed on to the landlord for them to choose. None of this whole apartment taken before even the open inspection has ended.    Pretty interesting to see your experiences on the process.

Yes! The windows! I never thought about what way my windows faced either. It was just never a priority. I had more important concerns like cost and square footage and neighborhood. But I have the opposite problem, I work nights and sleep in the day. So having windows that face east or west was just hell. Half the day was WAY too bright and WAY too hot in the summer. I got blackout curtains etc but if I accidentally fell asleep before setting everything up I had a horrible wake up call a few hours later that ruined my day. Still, I just accepted it. Then I moved into my new place and by accident got a north facing window with natural insulation from the brick walls I choose for ascetic.  I couldn't be happier, it makes SUCH a difference. The light is mild, even, and the same all day, and the temp doesn't fluctuate much (I live in LA). So I agree, if you have a choice, everyone should think about their lifestyle and needs when it comes to light.

I toured 16 apartments, but I still felt I couldâ€™ve asked more questions, looked for certain things! I will know better for next time! I was able to wait 2-3 days to decide. For the record I pay $1925 for a one bedroom in Washington Heights. There are definitely cheaper options but youâ€™re less likely to find them on StreetEasy. Most apartments are more money than that. Brokers fees were made illegal but then I heard they changed that...so idk.

I would like to point out that if you aren't looking in downtown Manhattan, you can get much more space for the same amount of money! I live uptown, and you can pay the amount that Ashley was looking at, and get around double the space. It's all about where you want to live and what you are looking for!  I would rather have more space and have a 20-30 minute commute to get downtown, than get less space in the most popular neighborhoods. But that's just me.
